description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of naked woman squatting (fecundity figure). A pregnant(?) woman, seated with legs wide apart. She is naked except for a sleeved garment with tight cuffs that presumably crossed her shoulders. The arms are bent at the elbow and both hands are raised just above her shoulders; the right hand is shown palm outwards and the left hand holds a small pot. She has anklets or, more likely, short boots. Her face is largely broken away, and her hair is parted in the centre, falling in locks onto her shoulders. She wears a large tightly woven and bound wreath, with lotus buds with phallic appearance rising on top. After the figure left the mould, and before firing, the vagina and the anus were pierced in areas marked with raised edges. The back is plain, with a circular vent. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of man with amphora. The upper part of a figure of a man, whose face tends towards the grotesque and who is naked (at least from the waist up), with hair receding at the temples showing beneath a pointed cap. He rests his cheek on his right hand and appears to be asleep. However, he holds an amphora on his left shoulder. The back is plain except for the point of his cap and the point of the amphora. Hollow, from two-piece mould, with traces of a white dressing mainly on the front, with touches of a pinkish-red paint on the flesh areas and a minute spot of blue paint on the brim of the cap. Brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Isis cradling Harpocrates. The back is plain and an edge of the circular vent survives. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Brown Nile silt with grey core, abundant fine gold mica, dung or clay pellets and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of hand-modelled torso. The torso of a seated female (?) figure; the arms, legs and head are lost, the head was made separately and socketed into a rounded cavity at the top of the body. The body was hand-modelled and is of crude rectangular form, with small added breasts and three horizontal ridges above the gouged-out navel; the pubic triangle was also applied and part of it is lost with the legs. At the rear a deep vertical groove indicates the spine. The body is finished off square at the bottom, but the pose of the legs is not determinable. The arms, now missing, were added to the body. Again, it cannot be certainly determined how the arms were arranged, except differences in the fired surface probably show that they were close to the sides of the torso, perhaps with the hands on the sides of the hips. Red Nile silt with a thick grey core and abundant gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value:
Green mudstone figure of a bull.

The horns of the bull are now lost, but a spiral pattern of its hide is visible at the forehead and with thin incised lines around its ears and at the top of the head. The body is large and heavy with its musculature clearly delineated across its legs and back. The body is elongated and the limbs are strong and thick.

There are chips to the eyes, snout and tail of the animal, and the lower legs are missing. The object is supported on a slim modern base.

description.value: Head and upper body of yellowish white limestone male figure, standing, wearing chiton and himation; painted. Areas around the right eye, nose, chin and the back of the right hand are chipped. The break runs from below the right elbow to the left wrist. Marks of fine chiselling are visible on the back of the head. Traces of black paint remain on the hair (back): small dark marks on the back (fire?).The cloth width of the himation, slung over the left shoulder, is very slim; thus the edge of the cloth below, which falls from the back to the front, is almost entirely visible. A fold buckles diagonally from the right elbow. A fine groove runs almost parallel to the mantle's neck line, thus creating the impression of a broad v-neck. The hair is rendered cap-like on the calvarium, its edge on the forehead is a horizontal line terminating at the ears and falls behind the large ears onto the shoulders in a bag-like fashion. The back is very flat except for the horizontal groves which separate hair and back or respectively the bend where the hair touches the neck. The back of the calvarium is rounded off.

description.value: Torso of terracotta male dwarf figure.  A figure of a dwarf in a striding pose, modelled in the round. He wears a rolled-up cloth round his waist, hitched on the left side. There was very probably no plinth and the lower part of what is likely to be a suspension-lug is applied between the upper shoulder-blades. Hollow; two-piece mould: the waist-cloth was applied after the figure left the mould, and the arms also may be additions; from a mark on the waist cloth it is likely that the phallus was erect (and applied).   Micaceous red-brown Nile silt, covered with an off-white dressing painted drab yellow. A modern hole has been bored underneath to mount the object on a stand.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Harpokrates.  Harpokrates, naked and standing against a pier to his left, on a low, plain-fronted plinth. His head is shaven except for a side-lock, he has two fingers to his mouth, and has a large pendent phallus. He has a ribbon round his head, holding two lotus buds on the top. A round-bottomed, two-handled pot is held in the crook of his left arm. The back is plain, but for a small circular depression for an unpierced vent.  Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt with a brown surface. The figure has cracked in places during firing. The front bears traces of a white dressing, with some also on the back. His sidelock is painted black and his head-ribbon has traces of green, but its buds are painted pink (one of the buds was damaged before the paint was applied); there is a black band below the lower moulding of the pier’s capital.

description.value:
Fragmentary sandstone figure dedicated by an official named Seneferu, the upper body now lost.

The statue is broken from the waist, with a slim portion of his torso intact. He wears a long kilt and his forearms are placed flat against his upper legs. The throne name of king Amenemhat II is inscribed across the top of the legs, framed between Seneferu's hands. Further incised text is placed across the clothing on the lower legs and records Sneferu's name, his role as overseer of the boat, and the name of his mother Meket. The legs are broad and the feet of the figure are bare. On the reverse are the remains of a slim back-pillar. There is no indication of any further incised text around the sides of the seat or across the statue base.

The left hand is damaged, and both forearms have large cracks visible along the stone surface. There are a number of small abrasions to the stone surface around the edges of the base and top of the seat.

The statue is broken from the waist, with a slim portion of his torso intact. He wears a long kilt and his forearms are placed flat against his upper legs. The throne name of king Amenemhat II is inscribed across the top of the legs, framed between Seneferu's hands. Further incised text is placed across the clothing on the lower legs and records Sneferu's name, his role as overseer of the boat, and the name of his mother Meket. The legs are broad and the feet of the figure are bare. On the reverse are the remains of a slim back-pillar. There is no indication of any further incised text around the sides of the seat or across the statue base.

The left hand is damaged, and both forearms have large cracks visible along the stone surface. There are a number of small abrasions to the stone surface around the edges of the base and top of the seat.

description.value: Faience figure, probably of a sphinx or a siren; appears to have been glazed (now mostly eroded away). On oval base some glaze survives, now missing all colour, originally green.The surface is very worn and the object very fragile. The head is missing.   An 'animal' is seated in a frontal position, it's posture is erect and above the front legs it has two large breasts which are uneven in terms of proportion and position. The belly looks rather slim on the right side, and far more voluptuous on the left. Visible features suggest a lion-bodied creature. The right front leg is in advance of the left. The lion's tail curves up and back  round the right haunch of the animal.   The neckline is not quite clear and the upper part of the back looks rather large, in fact, the object which emerges could be the bottom and back of a human figure seated on the animal's shoulders. The right foot and lower leg of the figure point forward, passing down along the shoulder and breast of the animal, and a short cloak is shown on the left side of the figure at the back.

description.value: Grey limestone statuette of a young huntsman.  Young huntsman; the left foot and part of the right restored, also parts of the bow and left hand. Rejoined at neck, knee and base.  A youth standing on an unevenly worked plinth, left leg advanced, both heels are on the ground. He wears a close fitting Cypriot cap with turned up ear-pieces, a short chiton with short sleeves, tied at the waist and tanged at the lower edge, and with an overfold falling in flaps on either side. Over each shoulder is slung a pair of animals; on the right, a young boar in front, a hare behind; on the left, the same animals in reversed position. The right arm hangs stiffly at the side, holding arrows; the left arm is bent up, holding a bow which is depicted as a disc in the shape of a segment of a circle. The feet are bare from the knees; the stone between them is not cut away. The kneecap is eye-shaped.  The face is square and rather large in comparison with the rest of the body, the eyes are large and almond-shaped, with projecting pupils; the mouth is straight, the nose worn away.  Down the back of the right leg is an inscription.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Bes. Bes, or a priest in a religious procession wearing a mask of Bes. He walks to right, carrying against his left shoulder a statuette of an Egyptian god or king. He wears a brief tunic with short sleeves, tied at the waist, from below which his phallus emerges to reach to the ground, and he holds a small round pot against his right side; an unidentified object lies by his left foot: it may be the head of an animal, turned to front, the rear end of which emerged behind Bes’s right leg, but is now largely lost. The statuette against his shoulder stands stiffly in an Egyptian manner, with its arms by its sides, wearing a short kilt. Its head is lost, as also is most of the Bes crown. The group stands on a plain, flat-faced plinth, broken. The back is plain, with a circular vent. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of woman supporting amphora on head. The upper part of a hydrophoros (watercarrier), broken at waist. She stands looking slightly towards her right, holding a jug on her head with her upraised right arm. The weight is cushioned by a pad. There may be the letter delta incuse on the jug. Her hair has a central parting and the locks are brushed to each side; there are indications that a sakkos was worn. She is dressed in a short-sleeved chiton with a deep V neckline, girdled just below her breasts. The back is plain. Hollow, from two-piece mould, then painted with traces of pink paint on jug and cloth by left breast. Orange-brown Nile silt with abundance fine gold mica and sparse dung and white inclusions <1mm. Discolouration and surface damage caused by subsequent burning.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure leaning on shield. A cleruch leaning on a Gaulish shield with a central spine. He is dressed mainly in civilian garb, a short belted tunic with sleeves, but with a chlamys fastened at the right shoulder and draped over his left side, an end of which trails over his wrist to dangle over the top of the shield. His right arm is akimbo, the hand resting on his waist. The left leg, much hidden by the shield, is lost below its edge, and the right leg is bent at the knee: he may wear a high boot. He is clean shaven, with the hair brushed back above and falling at the sides, with small bunches below the ears: he may be a Gaul, although cleruchs of other ethnic groups used the oval Gaulish shield. The plinth is broken away and the back is plain, with a circular vent. Hollow, from two-piece mould, with minute traces of white dressing on the front. Brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica, and occasional white inclusions.

description.value: Fragment from the left arm of a basalt statue of a male official.  The arm is broken just below the crook of the elbow and at the upper arm below the shoulder. Across the upper arm of the stone surface a portion of a carved cartouche records the name of Shepenwepet II, who acted as God’s Wife of Amun during the 25th Dynasty. The size of the arm may suggest that the original statue was around life-size, however based on the small fragment which has survived, it is not possible to determine the original statue type.  There are several chips and scratches visible across the stone surface.

description.value:
Fragmentary head of a sandstone male figure.

He wears a short wig that is set high on the forehead. His ears are placed high on the side of the head and appear oversized. His eyes are narrow with a thick incised line at the lower eyelid, and the inner corners of his eyes are deep set. The nose appears broad though the surface is worn, and the mouth is comparatively small. His lips are also damaged, though the right outer corner appears flat and the lips were likely pursed. At the chin is a broad false beard, now chipped along the edges. Part of the smooth surface of the upper body is intact, with little definition between the neck and chest area.

The figure is broken from the back of the wig, and the surface of the face and front of the wig on both sides now heavily worn. The object is supported on a modern rectangular base.

description.value: Dark grey limestone figure of a youth.  Draped youth sitting on a high-backed throne with arm-rests just about indicated and a footstool. His face is worn; his cheekbones are broad and portrusive, the chin pronounced. He is wearing a Cypriot conical cap with lappets and a button-like edge. Underneath the hair is falling in a broad mass with a pouch-like edge down to the shoulders. He is wearing a long wide chiton and an over-garment covering both shoulders and crossing from the left shoulder to the right knee, the under-garment reaching down to the bare feet. The right hand, wrapped in the cloak, is clenched in front of the breast, the left is resting on the arm-rest with the fingers hanging loosely. His body is slender with broad shoulders; the arms are very long with slender forearms and small hands; apart from the head the figure is worked rather flat with little depth. The left top of the throne is missing; the sides and back are flat, neither carefully smoothed nor straightened.
